2: Too many of you agree with my stance. Thus, you take me seriously. Again, the problem was with my audience. *shrug* Live and learn.<br>
<br>
Ghie, you made an extremely outrageous arguement, yes, but the problem is THAT was my whole point. I personally play with a circle of RL friends who berate me for getting my epic 3 months after them, not being 60 5 months after they hit it, not being a second AA title already, or not having a 55+ alt and lvl 60 main. Sad but true. You can say all you want that the game isn't driven by uberness, but my personal experience says otherwise. If you're wondering what I do with my time, and why I'm not at that level, I'm a tradeskiller. Time sink anyone? (My own fault, of course).<br>
<br>
Your post, meant in jest, turned out to be true. If you can't see that then you are playing with your eyes closed. Why go to Vex Thall (huge time sink to even kill Emperor) if you can be perfectly happy milling around in normal zones?<br>
<br>
Defining uberness is difficult. I tried my best to give it a definition along the lines of a disease or sickness. That seems to be what it is in many cases. Uber people often don't associate much with non uber people (they'd rather be in uber zones with their own type.) On the other hand, I would classify a large percentage of people who frequent these boards as uber. It's not exclusive. I can go on and on about what it is and isn't, but it's too hard to define. I wouldn't call it being able to solo something better than anyone else. For casters that really does not apply at all. But being able to take on something others can only dream of through your equipment and coordination with others, is uberness. It isn't just gear, it is skill, communication, obedience (to the raid leader), and accepting your role. You don't see many crappy players out there in Vex Thall, or killing Seru.<br>
<br>
I'll learn from my mistakes on my next attempt. Like I said, I'm an amateur. I'll take most of this as constructive criticism.<br>
<br>
Ares out.<br>
