 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ughie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ghie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 434<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/2/02 7:57:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3447.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Uberitis</span><hr size=1> So, I've been thinking...<br>
<br>
(little voice says 'uh-oh')<br>
<br>
Really, all I have done is educate people about satire. And, yes, I went back and read my original post and there are enough arguements in there that most people would recognize as outrageous to maintain the satire genre.<br>
<br>
But, aside from expressing the view that 'uber' is not more important than the social aspects of this game, I didn't really cover the discussion of 'Uber'.<br>
<br>
(/em Dons the asbestos-lined cloak.)<br>
<br>
Some of you know which guild I am in, some of you don't. Most of you don't care. It is generally a fallacy that all that the high end guilds care about is loot. The reality is that they are focused on accomplishments. Sometimes they want to be first to do something, but more frequently they just want to do something bigger than they have done before.<br>
<br>
Sure, loot is part of the motivation, but it is rarely the primary motivation for the guild. However, loot is important to successful raids. Better AC, better weapons, better resists, more mana and more mana flow all contribute to the success of a raid.<br>
<br>
That said...the players in the higher end guilds are usually not there because they wanted to be uber. They are there because they have already done everything that the other guilds can offer them. They are there because, with their playstyle and playtimes, their character progression made them peers with the players in those guilds. <br>
<br>
On the subject of friendship vs. uber. Honestly, I know very few people that have disdained social relationships in favor of a 'better' guild. The last three times I changed guilds, I did it with all of my friends. Each guild change was based entirely on interpersonal changes, not on any desire to become more uber. We chose the guild we wanted to be part of based on what we had done and what we hadn't done yet. We wanted a guild that could organize and do things as a whole rather than a loose bunch of friends whose only link is the tag above their heads.<br>
<br>
Some people prefer to play the game as a team in a goal oriented environment. They enjoy the comraderie developed by playing together and accomplishing things together. They make lasting friends by always having the same people fighting at their sides. Few things in life make more lasting, unconditional friendships than fighting at someones side in battle. These people usually find themselves in the high end guilds. In reality there is little place in these guilds for the loot driven or level driven people. Most of the time, while a part of these guilds, players are working purely for goals of the guild.<br>
<br>
Other people like to play in a more casual, relaxed, less structured environment. They like to log on and be able to chose for themselves what to do for the day. These people will eventually find guilds that support this style of play.<br>
<br>
There are guilds out there for every style of play.<br>
<br>
Uber-envy starts at the few people that are purely jealousy driven people. But jealousy becomes contagious when these people start talking. They convince others that everyone deserves the same share of the spoils, regardless of playstyle. They make people believe that the high end gamers are getting more than their share. People start to listen and they start to notice the difference in the characters. People allow their own minds to be poisoned with this jealousy. They want to have what the other people have...but not all of them want to play or can play in the style that earns those rewards.<br>
<br>
Is that Lamentation suddenly not good enough to kill frogs with anymore because you heard about a Swiftblade of Zek? Is that Swiftblade any less effective than it was because someone has a 15/17 weapon? Should you have any less fun in OS or Velks because someone else is in Vex Thal? Does your armor work any less effective than it did because someone has a Chestplate of Vindication?<br>
<br>
In the previous guild I was in, too many people wanted the high end rewards without the high end commitment. Too many people wanted only to attend raids where they had a high chance of personal reward. These people had uberitis. The high end game isnt about that. It is about selflessly working on a team towards a goal with the reward being success in itself and only occasionly having the material rewards fall your way.<br>
<br>
Of course there is also the jealousy from people whose lifesyle doesnt allow them the same time commitment to the game as that twenty year old who still lives with his parents who dont mind him living there and playing EQ all day...Or they prefer to spend some of their nights in Real life social situations...Yet they get jealous about people who chose to spend all their waking moments in EQ...They can't grasp that EQ doesn't reward responsible life decisions by giving you faster rewards in game for less of a playtime commitment. People need to understand that the rewards for a responsible real life are found in real life.<br>
<br>
Since I started playing EQ, I have maintained normal jobs during normal hours. I keep my kids fed and clothed and have a nice house and make sure they are learning all the right things. I play mostly after they are asleep. Even when I was unemployed my playtimes were usually late at night. My current main character wasnt even created till 9 months after EQ went live. Yet, some would call me uber and there are people who drool over Ghie's gear. But I didn't get where I am by playing 24/7 or by pushing for it. (Okay I pushed a little for my epic.) I got it by showing up to help the guilds I was in at the time attain their goals. I got it by choosing to play in guilds where raiding as a guild was the norm.<br>
<br>
Jealous people see the 'uber' high end game as the gear and the levels.<br>
<br>
Those of us playing the high end game know that its about teamwork, working for the good of the whole, knowing that each part benefits when the whole is stronger.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><CENTER>G
MF Virtuoso</CENTER>

