<br>
For me, there's nothing in EQ quite like the thrill of a close fight, of taking down a bad guy when you think your chances are slim.  That sort of situation can be found in a single group, but most often I've encountered it on raids.  There's something amazing about seeing a group of people come together and succeed using text as the main method of communicating often-intricate strategies.<br>
<br>
Do I have neat toys?  Sure.<br>
But I also have loads of memories of first fights and nasty wipes, and ongoing jokes.  Silly pics of myself in front of dead dragons or goofy-looking 4-armed robe things. <br>
<br>
Do I think of myself as uber?  Not really, considering I'm often fighting alongside, and loosely comparing myself to, some of the best warriors in the game.  Do I think those warriors are uber?  In some ways, yes, but I've also seen their personalities and know that in a lot of ways, they're just like me.  I think some of the problems discussed here come in when you try to lump people into general groups, whether based on gear, guild, playtime, or any other factor, without taking into account actual personalities or relationships.  Maybe that's the whole point of discussion here, but I don't know because I've rambled now and lost my train of thought :)<br>
<br>
At any rate, I thought Ghie's post was pretty well-reasoned.  Maybe because that's also been my experience and I'm biased.<br>
