<br>
What you are describing is not uberitis or anything so limited.<br>
<br>
You are describing general human behavior.<br>
<br>
We, as humans, see thing from the perspective of our selves.<br>
<br>
It is actually a very rare human who can see someone who lives in a home worth a tenth of the value of our home, someone who drives a car of lesser value than our own, or makes less money than us as an equal. <br>
<br>
We, as humans, percieve the differences in our statii based on wealth and age.<br>
<br>
Fifty year olds get upset when their old boss retires and is replaced by a pimple faced kid. But that kid put the time and money into getting his doctorate in business...<br>
<br>
We see people driving around in fancier cars and spending half their work day at the golf course and without even meeting them we paste an attitude on them.<br>
<br>
People who were our friends in college disappear when we enter the real world and one of our professions makes $50,000 more than the other, even though we only live two blocks apart. <br>
<br>
People who were our friends disappear when we get married...because that too is a status difference.<br>
<br>
Luckily, as humans, we can control our thoughts and feelings once we are aware of them. We don't have to be prejudiced against people of different statii.<br>
<br>
Go up to your boss someday and ask him what advice he can give you on how to succeed as he has. Some bosses will sit down and talk with you. Others will give you a one line response.<br>
<br>
Even when made aware of our natural prejudices to people of different statusii, most people won't change. They are comfortable with their social classes. They feel no need to develop new associations with people of lower classes and they strive to get promoted, join country clubs, get better homes and cars...<br>
<br>
This uberitis you describe is not something limited to the game. Remember that everyone you meet in game is human. <p><CENTER>G
MF Virtuoso</CENTER>

